.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.0" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME
hsh \- a simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh
[\fIcommand\fR [\fIargument ...\fR]]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX shell that reads and executes commands from standard input.
It replicates the core behavior of
.B /bin/sh
and supports both interactive and non-interactive modes.

In interactive mode,
.B hsh
displays a prompt
.B ($)
and waits for the user to enter a command.

In non-interactive mode, commands are read from a pipe or a file.

.SH INVOCATION
.TP
.B Interactive mode
Launch the shell directly:
.IP
.nf
$ ./hsh
($)
.fi

.TP
.B Non-interactive mode
Pipe commands into the shell:
.IP
.nf
$ echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
$ cat file_of_commands | ./hsh
.fi

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS

.TP
.B exit [\fIstatus\fR]
Exit the shell. If a numeric
.I status
is provided, the shell exits with that status code.

.TP
.B env
Print all environment variables of the current process to standard output.

.SH PATH RESOLUTION
When a command is entered without an absolute or relative path,
.B hsh
searches each directory listed in the
.B PATH
environment variable in order, and executes the first matching executable found.

If no matching executable is found,
.B hsh
prints an error message to standard error:

.IP
.nf
./hsh: 1: command: not found
.fi

.SH EXECUTION
For each command entered,
.B hsh
creates a child process using
.BR fork (2),
then replaces the child's image with the requested program using
.BR execve (2).
The parent process waits for the child to terminate using
.BR wait (2).

.SH EOF / END OF FILE
If
.B Ctrl+D
is entered in interactive mode, the shell exits gracefully, same as typing
.BR exit .

.SH ERROR HANDLING
Error messages printed by
.B hsh
match those of
.B /bin/sh
in format, with the difference that the program name reflects
.B argv[0]
as passed to the shell:

.IP
.nf
./hsh: 1: qwerty: not found
./././hsh: 1: qwerty: not found
.fi

.SH COMPILATION
.nf
gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89 *.c -o hsh
.fi

.SH EXAMPLES

.TP
Run a command:
.IP
.nf
($) /bin/ls
hsh main.c shell.c
.fi

.TP
Run a command with arguments:
.IP
.nf
($) /bin/echo Hello World
Hello World
.fi

.TP
Display environment variables:
.IP
.nf
($) env
PATH=/usr/local/sbin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/sbin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/bin
HOME=/root
...
.fi

.TP
Exit the shell:
.IP
.nf
($) exit
$
.fi

